   },
   {
    "text": "The Shogun is the military dictator of Japan. Nominally appointed by the Emperor, The Shogun is the de facto ruler of the Empire. The office of shogun is in practice hereditary, though over the course of the history of Japan several different clans held the position. All Daimyō serve directly under the Shogun. Tokugawa Yoshinobu is the Shogun. He must be referred to as \"Ue-sama\".",
    "contextConfig": {
     "suffix": "\n",
     "tokenBudget": 2048,
     "budgetPriority": -400
    },
    "displayName": "Shogun",
    "keys": [
     "Shogun"
    ],
    "category": "209bc66a-8a48-46f2-7551-58e1d47bbee1"
   },
   {
    "text": "Kyōto is the capital of Japan. Kyōto has temples such as the Kyomizu, and the Imperial Palace. Locations in Kyoto are: the Gion Yūkaku district, Kyomizu Temple, the Imperial Palace, Shijôgahara, and Togetsukyôenji.",
    "contextConfig": {
     "suffix": "\n",
     "tokenBudget": 2048,
     "budgetPriority": -400
    },
    "displayName": "Kyōto",
    "keys": [
     "Kyōto",
     "Kyoto"
    ],
    "category": "b555dc8f-98e5-463a-65d5-1d032eeaa9a1"
   },
   {
    "text": "Shijōgahara is a large park located on the north side of the Kamo River, near the center of Kyoto. It is famous for its beauty and tranquility. It has been used as a training ground for martial arts since the 14th century. Shijōgahara is the site of many duels between samurai, and the grounds were considered to be off-limits to commoners.",
    "contextConfig": {
     "suffix": "\n",
     "tokenBudget": 2048,
     "budgetPriority": -400
    },
    "displayName": "Shijôgahara",
    "keys": [
